{"id":"1801.02965","submitter":"Alberto Pezzotta","authors":"Alberto Pezzotta, Matteo Adorisio, Antonio Celani","title":"Chemotaxis emerges as the optimal solution to cooperative search games","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 98, 042401 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.98.042401","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Cooperative search games are collective tasks where all agents share the same\ngoal of reaching a target in the shortest time while limiting energy\nexpenditure and avoiding collisions. Here we show that the equations that\ncharacterize the optimal strategy are identical to a long-known\nphenomenological model of chemotaxis, the directed motion of microorganisms\nguided by chemical cues. Within this analogy, the substance to which searchers\nrespond acts as the memory over which agents share information about the\nenvironment. The actions of writing, erasing and forgetting are equivalent to\nproduction, consumption and degradation of chemoattractant. The rates at which\nthese biochemical processes take place are tightly related to the parameters\nthat characterize the decision-making problem, such as learning rate, costs for\ntime, control, collisions and their trade-offs, as well as the attitude of\nagents toward risk. We establish a dictionary that maps notions from\ndecision-making theory to biophysical observables in chemotaxis, and vice\nversa. Our results offer a fundamental explanation of why search algorithms\nthat mimic microbial chemotaxis can be very effective and suggest how to\noptimize their performance.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 9 Jan 2018 14:52:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 16 May 2018 16:35:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-10-10"}
